## OVERVIEW:
This program is an implementation of a Turing Machine in java, where
the TMSimulator class reads a file containing an encoding of a Turing
Machine with a Tape string (empty or with a start string) which is
used to step through the Turing Machine. Each transition in the TM is
mapped according to the encoding specifications and the simulator steps
through each state until halted. When halted, it prints out the contents
of the Tape string.

The turing machine can move left or right on the tape and uses the transition table to read from the tape and move between states. All states have a valid transition for every character in the alphabet of the tape.

## INCLUDED FILES:
* TMSimulator.java - source file
* TMTape.java - source file
* TMTransition.java - source file
* README - this file

## COMPILING AND RUNNING:
From the directory containing all source files and files to 
be passed to simulator, compile the driver class (and all 
dependencies) with the command:
* \$ javac TMSimulator.java

Run the compiled class file with the command:
* \$ java tm.TMSimulator [file name].txt

Console output will give the results after the program finishes.

Formatted .txt file should follow the format:
Line 1: The number of states
Line 2: The size of the alphabet (excluding blank)
Line 3 to n: Transitions using the format (toState, write, move L/R)
    ex: 1, 1, R - Goes to state 1, writes 1 to the tape, and moves the tape head right.
Line n (final line): The starting tape, leave blank to make the starting tape blank.

## PROGRAM DESIGN AND IMPORTANT CONCEPTS:
The TMSimulator is responsible for reading command line input
and parsing the file contents to populate the Tape and the
transitions of the encoded TM. After, it simulates stepping 
through the TM until the machine halts, where it then prints to
the console the Tape string.

The TMTape class contains methods to read the value at the head
of the string, write at the head, create the staring tape string
from file input, and print the tape. The tape first checks if it
will be moving left or right, writes the given value at the head,
and increases or decrements the head count depending on the movement.
An ArrayList is used to represent the infinite tape with random indexing
to allow the tape to shift as needed to make space for newly written
values.

TMTransition contains the methods to parse the input from file for 
each transition in the TM. Using the format of next state, write character,
move direction. It also contains methods to get each field from the
transition.

## TESTING:
The program assumes that all files to be tested are included in the root
path of the simulator, but it does check the length of the input
to ensure all fields are included in the command line. It also
catches file not found exceptions that could occur from bad input.

The main source of testing was using the provided test files (file0,2,5.txt), and comparing our output to the expected output in the project specifications. We also printed out additional info in TMSimulator's output to make sure things like the tape head and output length were matching the expectations, which we later removed so our output would match the grader.

I also wrote an additional test file which I tweaked to try out edge cases, such as a single state TM. This helped me catch a few bugs which weren't apparent using the three provided files.

## DISCUSSION:

Conceptualizing the machine was the most difficult part for me, as
I struggled to grasp the logic of the TM as a whole. I was unsure how
to break the TMSimulator into its parts and be able to simulate stepping 
through after parsing the file. Thankfully, Dean wrote the main logic
and the Tape and Transition classes, which I was able to look at for
guidance for the stepping logic. Debugging was also helpful for understanding
the logic of the TMSimulator, as I could watch how the tape was being created/
added to as the program stepped through. After the initial hurdle of understanding all the programs pieces, it was much simpler to fine
tune the logic and debug the program. -- Haylee

My main concern was fully understanding the project specifications, I tried to make my initial changes adaptable enough that if the implementation wasn't fully correct it could be modified. Haylee was able to take my groundwork and get things finalized, and made the necessary changes to meet the grader's expectations after communicating with the professor. Initially, I made TMState a class rather than TMTransition, but I realized that the states themselves don't need to contain information here, it seemed more intuitive to just save the state number as a variable since we know the state names are integers and the final state is the highest number. I pivoted to having TMTransition be a class instead. I chose to use an ArrayList for reading the tape, and a HashTable for the transition table. I chose an ArrayList for the tape because it has a get() of O(1), and its worst case is adding to the start of the array, which doesn't happen much in the test files. A goal of mine was to keep the overall structure of this project simple to maximize runtime, so I relied a lot on the known confines of this program's TMs.  If I had more time, I would try to find a more efficient datastructure than ArrayList for the purpose of the tape. --Dean

